Recent Developments:
In January 2023, Hikvision launched the MinMoe Iris Recognition Terminal, a new iris recognition device that is designed for high-level access security. The MinMoe Iris Recognition Terminal is said to be able to identify users in less than 1 second, even in low-light conditions.
In February 2022, Iris ID announced that it had partnered with Suprema to integrate its iris recognition technology with Suprema’s access control systems. This partnership will allow Suprema to offer its customers a more secure and convenient way to control access to their facilities.
In March 2022, Aware announced that it had raised $25 million in Series C funding. This funding will be used to accelerate the development of Aware’s iris recognition technology and to expand its market reach.
In April 2022, NEC announced that it had developed a new iris recognition system that is said to be more accurate and reliable than previous systems. The new system is said to be able to identify users even in challenging conditions, such as low-light and high-contrast environments.
In May 2022, Safran announced that it had partnered with Thales to develop a new iris recognition system for use in the aviation industry. The new system is said to be more secure and reliable than previous systems and is designed to meet the strict security requirements of the aviation industry.
